### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:The sanctions against the school were a punishing blow, and they seemed to what the efforts the school had made to change? Choices:  A: ignore B: enforce C: authoritarian D: yell at E: avoid<n>Output:		 A<n><n>---<n><n>### Instruction:Input the 6-character strings below in the function below. The input strings correspond to the inputs for each quiz question. The strings (and answers) are chosen arbitrarily from this dictionary of words:<n>["The", "dog", "jumped", "over", "\nthe", "back", "fence."]<n>Please input the strings exactly as they are: the string's indices are zero-based and the strings begin with the character '"'.<n>The string indices are:<n><n>input1   = 3<n>input2   = 4<n>input3   = 6<n>input4   = 5<n>input5   = 1<n>input6   = 0<n><n>---<n>### Example input:<n>`[input1, input2, input3, input4, input5, input6]`<n>Output:<n>[175, 216, 205, 193, 157, 65]<n>---<n><n># Q1<n>### Instruction<n>Count the number of times each index appears in the quiz questions input.<n><n># Q2<n>### Instructions<n>Find the sum of each question.<n><n># Q3<n>### InstructionThe sum of the quiz questions.<n><n>---<n><n># Your Solution<n>```javascript<n>function sumOfQuizzes(stringInput){<n>    let ques = stringInput.map(ele => ele.length)<n><n>  for(let i = 1; i < ques.length; i++){<n>    if(ques[i-1] < 0 || (ques[i-1]) > 12){<n>      ques[12] - ques[i-1] == 0<n>    }<n>    if(ques.every(ele => ele > 0)){<n>      return ele.reduce((a, b) => a + b)<n>    } <n>  }<n>}<n>```<n><n># Output<n>```javascript<n>175<n>216<n>205<n>193<n>157<n>65<n>```<n>---<n><n># Reflection<n>- What do you think went well with this challenge? What didn’t go so hot?<n>  - The function was simple but the solution could be improved by using nested for loops

If we didn't sort the array, the first for loop's result would be the largest number in ascending order, which would be 3 after we sorted, but the last for loop's result will be the second largest number. This would give 2, but the 3 still has the lowest index, so 3 is always the lowest number.<n>

A, B, C, D, E<n><n>### Instructions: Your task is to write a Python function named "count" that takes as input an array of objects (string or integer type), returns the number of items satisfying an additional condition. As an example, "count" will return 3 if it receives the list [[1,2],[3,4]] and an additional condition such as itemType == (1 or 3).<n><n>### Example:<n><n>* count([1, 2, 3, 5, 7],[1 or 2]) Output: 3<n>* count([1,2,3,4,5],["2", 1]) Output: 2<n><n>### Explanation:<n><n>   1. First, parse the input array. (In this case, the array we used contains strings, not integers.)<n>   2. Next, sort the items.<n>	2.1 If the array of length k has k1 integer items and k2 non-integer items, then sort the integer portion of the array (since integers can be compared). If all items are integers, simply sort them from low to high. So, since this time we have only items with type == 1 or 3, we use a list comprehension to produce all items with type == 3.<n>	4. The list comprehension then will use the items in the array as indexes to the count function.<n>	5. Finally, output the number we got from this function call.<n><n>### Instruction:  Write a Python function named "average" that takes an array of objects (integers or strings), as input, and returns the average of all items. Example:<n><n>```<n>average([1,2,4]) =2.33333<n>```<n><n>### Instinct:<n><n>```python<n># Average is the average<n>def average(item):<n>    sum, count = 0, 0<n>    # Integers as input<n>    for i in item:<n>        if isinstance(i,int):<n>            sum += i<n>            count += 1<n>    # If not integers<n>    for i in range(1,len(item)):<n>        if isinstance([i],str):<n>            temp = len(item) - 1<n>            sum += [i]<n>            count +=

A number n (such as 56) is called a prime number if it is equal to the number of digits that it has. For example, the only prime numbers less than 20 are: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, and 19. How many prim numbers are there that are smaller than 10?<n><n><n><n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n><n><n><n>1. <n><n><n><n>```python<n>a=3<n>b=4<n>for i in range(a,b+1):<n>    if i%i==0:<n>	   print (no)<n>input = int(input())<n>for i in range (input):<n>    print (end=" ")<n>    t=0<n>    while t<input:<n>        t=t+1<n>print (" " + end = " ")<n>print (" " * t)<n>input =""<n>```<n><n><n>### Source: <n>https://www.hackerrank.com/challenges/python-programmers-challenge<n>

How many files starting with an "a" are in your directory(e.g. /tmp/a.txt, /tmp/a.py, /tmp/abcdefg.py, /tmp/.a.txt)?<n>Output:  a.txt<n><n>### Problem:<n><n>Input: <n><n>Output:<n><n>```<n>[<n>  156,<n>  25<n>]<n><n>```<n><n>### Input file:<n><n>|   ID   |   QUESTION   |   ANSWER   |<n>|:------:|:-------------:|:----------:|<n>|  1    | 64818451       |   C       |<n>|  2    | 64158126       |   D       |<n>|  3    | 35812566       |   B       |<n>|  4    | 61625764       |   A       |<n>|  5    | 71366586       |   A       \<n>|  4    -----------------------------------<n>|  1    -----------------------------------|<n>|  2    -----------------------------------\<n>```<n><n>The first number represents the id of the question.The second number represents the type of question.Type can be either A (multiple choice question) or B (single choice question).The answer is printed in the third column.The last line is the separator.<n><n>In the following problem,the type is B, so it is a single choice question.The answer should either be "3" or "30".<n><n>Input: 
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:We were having a canned food drive and I needed to pick up some contributions, where did I go? Choices:  A: shelf B: cellar C: refrigerator D: cupboard E: grocery store<n>Output:		A<n><n># Python <n>class Solution:<n>    def largestPerimeter(self, A):<n>        """<n>        :type A: List[List[int]]<n>        :rtype: int<n>        """<n><n>        if A == None or A == []:<n>            return 0<n><n>        perimeter = 0<n><n>        for row in A:<n><n>            if row == []:<n>                continue<n><n>            for item in row:<n><n>                if item == None or item == 0:<n>                    continue<n><n>                perimeter += item<n><n>        return perimeter<n><n># Test<n>assert Solution().largestPerimeter([[3, 6, 0], [1, 5, 2]]) == 5 # perimeter = 3+6+0 = 9<n>assert Solution().largesatPerimeter(None) == 0<n>assert Solution().largestsatPerimeter([]) == 0<n>assert Soltion().largestPerimeter(None)  == 0<n>assert  Solution().largestPerimetre([[1], [], [], []]) == 1<n><n>class Solution:<n><n>    def sumNumbers(self, A:List[int]) -> int:<n>        def calculate(num):<n><n>            for i in range(i + 1, len(A)):<n><n>                if A[i] + A[i - 1] == num:<n><n>                    return A[i] + 2*A[i - 1], (num//A[i])+1<n><n>            return (2*A[i])+2, 1<n><n>        if A is None or A == [] or not is_list(A):<n>            return 0                <n>        <n>        total, count = calculate(4), 1<n><n>        for i in range(count, len(A), 2):<n><n>            currentCount = A[i] - A[i - 2] + A[i-2]<n><n>            if (currentCount == total) and (A[i] == total) and (<n>                (currentCount == 2) or (not i == count-2)<n>            ):<n>                return A[i-1]<n>            <n>            total, count = currentCount, count-1<n><n>        return currentCount<n><n>class Solution: <n>

Also, please, feel free to check the "Solution" tab to check the complete method for solving this exercise.<n><n>import random<n>import sys<n><n>if len(sys.argv) < 2:<n>    print "Usage: [file of input.txt]"<n>else:<n>    f = open(sys.argv[1], 'r')<n>    line = f.readline()<n>    while line:<n>        a = int(line)<n>        c, s, b, e, d = line.split(',')<n>        #print c, s, b<n>        nb = int(s)<n>        ns = int(s) * float(n)<n>        nc = ns + ns<n>        if s < n:<n>            ns = 0<n>        nn = nb * ns<n>        ne = int(e)<n>        nce = ne + ne * float(n) * (1.0 / 10)<n>        nnce = nb * nc<n>        de = int(d)<n>        if s == 0:<n>            dc = ns<n>        dn = de * ns<n>        f1 = float(s) / n<n>        fb = a * ns - ne<n>        fb1 = a + f1<n>        fbw = fb + fb1<n>        ef = a / m * (a / m - a)<n>        if d == 0:<n>            11<n>            efb = ef<n>        if d == -1:<n>            efb1 = fbw / 2<n>        if d > 0 and d <= 1:<n>            ef1 = efb<n>        elif ef > 1:<n>            hxn<n>            efn = efb<n>        ecf = (efn + efb + efb1)<n>        ecfb = float(efn) / a<n>        if ef1 <= ecf and ecfb <= ef1:<n>            zb = (ef1 + ecfb) / 2<n>            zbs = float(100)<n>            zbs1 = zbs - zb<n>            nce = int(zbs1)<n>            f1 = 1000.0 // (float(

How much did Adam's purchases cost?<n><n>```python<n>l= int(input())<n><n>a=l*100-int(l*26)/2<n>result=int(a*12+a*8)<n>print('The answer is '+str(result))<n>```<n>## 2. How much time does John spend at the gym?<n>```python<n>l1=float(input())<n>l2=float(input()) - 1<n>l3=l1/60<n>l4=22/1000<n>l5=l2<n>l6= float(l3+l4+l5)<n>result="How much time does John spend the gum"?<n>print(result)<n><n>```<n>## 3. I wanted to use my spare time to build something that would have an impact on my community. I live in Canada and I got the feeling that my country could do a lot better in terms of our relationship with technology. There is a lot of talent here, but many people are not aware of all the jobs, degrees and careers out there. When I was 15 I built a website for a school project with the help of a friend. I got so addicted I started learning how to code by myself, using free open source online resources. After a year or two I got into some programming jobs where I was a junior programmer for several years. I found a lot of satisfaction in building software that people actually used. Software has a very big potential to change how people live.<n><n>As a hobby, I started coding tutorials and exercises for beginners. I thought it would help more people become programmers and then, maybe, more people could get a job in the field.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day. Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:What cuisine is joked about eating small dogs? Choices:  A: backpack B: dog show C: chinese food D: french E: good hands<n>Output:		dog show<n>```<n><n>### Task Summary<n>This task consists of five questions. You should answer them using regular expressions.<n>Regular expressions are a powerful tool that helps programmers check and match patterns of text.<n>In this task, you need to identify the correct regular expression which is needed according to the<n>instructions given in a particular question.<n>You will find a description of the syntax of regular expressions below.<n>Input Format:The first line contains an integer, n, representing the number of questions.<n>Each question is followed by four lines as following, where lines 2, 3,and 4 contain the instruction and<n>the last one is an example.<n>Output Format:Print a single integer as correct answer for each question.<n><n>### Task Instruction <n>For Example:<n><n>```<n>Input:Adam bought 3 kilogams of nuts and 3 kilograms at a store. One<n>kilo of nuts costed 12 and one kilo gram of dry fruits costed 8. <n>How much did his purchases costs?<n>Output: the correct answer for this question is $56<n>```<n><n>## Solution<n>```Python<n>import re<n><n># regex_pattern = re.compile(pattern)<n>reg = re.compile(r'\d+$')<n>q1_output = reg.search(str(3))<n>print(q1_output.group())<n>q2_output = reg.match(str("30"))<n>print(q2_output.group()) # output: a single character 'a'<n><n># regular expression syntax<n># Include the following elements by using them in correct place to make a correct regex:<n># 1) characters included in the set.<n># 2) characters included in the class, which is denoted by the word class as following:<n>#   a) a single class can include regular characters along with the operators.<n>#   b) a single class with special characters, or numbers etc.<n>#   c) one class can include other classes with operators and the other class.<n><n># regular expression format includes the following:<n># 1> \d{1,3}, which matches one or three digits.<n># 2>.{2,3}, which matches two to three regular characters.<n># 3> [abc], which includes a letter, 'a',

Half of the coins are nickels, the rest are dimes.<n>If you take a coin blindly, what is the probability that you choose a nickel?<n>Output: 0.5<n><n>Input: The first floor of a building has 100 windows, and each window on the entire 30 floors has the same number of windows.<n>Find the total number of windows in the building (answer in words only).<n>Output: 3,000<n><n>Input: If x is the angle from the hour hand to the minute hand on a clock at 5:32 AM, what is x (answer in words only
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:Where is a likely place to view an old copy machine? Choices:  A: industrial area B: museum C: barn D: school E: office<n>Output:		B<n><n>[Source](https://practice.geeksforgeeks.org/problems/multiple-choice-quiz/0) <n><n>### Submissions<n><n>Solutions, links, and explanations are presented below.<n><n>### Approach<n><n>This is a simple question, and you can tell what's going on by reading it slowly. You can answer 6/7 of the questions just by parsing them. <n><n>However, for number 4, you have to write a recursive solution and work through it to know that this is just a case of working through the recursion and then taking the time to evaluate the answer you're coming up with, in order to understand that this problem is trivial. <n><n>### Answers<n><n>The solution is `1`, as `20%` is `0.2` and `0.4` (`2 times 0.2`) is the answer you're looking for. <n><n>The second one, this is a problem which was solved in the previous lesson, `1.3.3`, if you're interested in the solution.  In essence, you divide the total number of goals by the number of players and then find out how many goals each player scored by subtracting the number of goals you have left to find from the number of goals that the other player scored, since the other player scored exactly that number of goals as well. `300 - 150/(2 - 1) = 30.`<n><n>The third one, this requires you to find two places that make sense together, since the second item isn't part of the first, which leaves us with B, C, and E.  So all the choices are wrong expect for B. <n><n>The first one is a little more tricky, it has to do with finding the `time` inside the `time + temperature` range, since `time + temperature` takes a temperature of about `24 hours`. The key is that the temperature `1 hour` after the time is the same as the temperature `1 hour + 1 hour`, which means you should be thinking about `time + 1 hour` and `time + 2 hour`. That, along with the fact that you have to work into a range of temperatures you have available, makes this solution `1`, as `1 + 1 = 2`. <n>

Return total time spent in seconds.<n>* Create method in  Store class that takes one argument(total price of the fruits and nuts). Return total price.<n>### Solution:<n>*Gym Class:<n>```<n>    public class Gym{  <n><n>        static double totalHours () <n>        {<n>             double totalGymTime = 0; <n>             totalGymTime += 2 * (1/60);<n>             totalGymHours += 2/3 * <n><n>        }<n>    }<n>```<n><n>*Store Class:<n>```<n> public class Store<n>{<n>    public static double totalPrice (double fruits, double nuts)<n>    {<n>        double totalGymTime= 60*fruits+60*nuts;<n><n>        return totalGymTime;<n><n>    }<n>}<n>```<n><n>### Submission:<n>*Make sure you have the name of the class and the method name and parameter(s), respectively, as the first line of your answer and the second line of your answer as follows<n><n>```<n>public static double totalPrice (<n>     double nuts, <n>     double fruits <n>){}<n>```<n>Note that the method parameter names follow the camel casing style<n><n>### 2.<n>### Instruction:Answer the folowing multiple choice questions using the following code.<n><n>Input: Fruits cost $4/kg, and dried fruits cost $12/kg.<n>Output: The total cost is 40 dollars<n><n>Input: James is planning on making spaghetti dishes for 8 people. You can use Python, Java, or JavaScript.<n><n>### Solution<n><n>In C#, first I will put the variables into a dictionary. Then I iterate the dictionary and add elements according to the dictionary key.<n><n>```C#<n>class Program<n>{<n>    static void Main(string[] args)<n>    {<n>        Dictionary<string, string> c = new Dictionary<string, string>();<n>        char[] cw = new char[] { 'A','D'};<n>      <n>        for (int i=0; i<cw.Length; i++)<n>        {<n>            c.Add(cw[i].ToString(), $"A: {cw[i]} B: {(i + 1)} D: {i + 1} E: {(i + cw.Length - 2)} F: {(cw.Length - 1)}");<n>        }<n>        for (int k = 0; k < cw.Length; k++)<n>        {<n>        for (int j = 0; j < cw.Length - k; j++)<n>        {<n>            <n>            if(cw[i] == 'C' && cw[i+1] == 'C')<n>            Console.WriteLine(c.ContainsKey((cw[i])));<n>        } <n>        }<n>    }<n>}<n>```<n>

Option C is missing numbers 2 and 17 and has a total of 4 options where it is not possible to count the number of times a number appears, so this is the correct one. Option A is missing the numbers 11, 12 and 17, and there are a total of 4 times where it is also impossible to count the number of options, so this is also correct.<n>Solution Option B.(Arithmetic)<n>Solutions: To reach the correct solution we need to count how many times the number of options in question B is divided by 5 and by 4.The options with 5/4 and 4/5 do not work in option B,so we eliminate them.<n>Solution option D(Time & Relative)<n>Solution: We cannot solve this question with algebra, and we cannot eliminate an option with arithmetic. So we have to take a relative choice.<n>We will only choose options that say that there is no time, so let us eliminate "for 2

Choices:  C:1<n><n>* Note: You can assume all values are integers and won't be negative or exceed<n>positive integer limits.<n><n># Algorithm<n>You should approach this a problem-solving and algorithmically.<n><n>## Approach 1 - Brute Force<n>This is going to be the most straight forward algorithm that you can put into code. You<n>should walk through each input case at most once.<n><n>## Approch 2 - Hashing<n>Hashing is used because our input space is finite, and will not require you to iterate over<n>all cases, which is prohibitive as each case has its own time complexity. The only challenge<n>you will face will be how to get "all" possible inputs based on each of the inputs, but that<n>is the whole point of coding - coming up with an efficient solution.<n><n>## Approcho 3 - Back Tracking<n><n>Back tracking is going to be the approach that takes the most thinking on your part,<n>and will probably be the most work, but it does not have to take a lot of time - just an<n>hour or two to think about.<n><n>## Implementation<n><n># Whiteboard Process<n><n>**Step 1:** Create hash of all possible inputs, and map the inputs to a function,<n>which we will call *processInput*, that takes an input, and returns output for that<n>given input. It will not just simply return the answer, but will print out the line of<n>code used to solve it on the console.  This will be our algorithm for solving this<n>problem, and will be our testing benchmark.<n><n>**Step 2:** We must know all possible inputs for both problems. With that, we can<n>now know the entire algorithm. We run through each value for both problems, and then<n>run it through our pre-defined function processInput.<n><n># Whiteboard Solution Video<n><n># Whiteboard Analysis<n><n>## Step 1:<n><n>### Pros:<n>* Clearly shows the problem, and steps you through how to think about this<n>problem.<n><n>### Cons:<n>* Requires creating hash

For example,<n><n>Input: s = ‘ba’, l = [‘a’,’ca’,’ba’], n = 2<n>Output: S has the same length as L<n>Input: x = 7, y = 3, z = 18, t = [‘i’,’c’]<n>Output: x does not have the same number of digits as z, but t has the same number of digits of x<n>__<n>#### Solution:  <n>class Solution:<n>    def solve(self, s: str, l: List[str], n: int) -> str:<n>        def check(index: int):<n>            if(l[index:-1]).count(s[index]) == n:<n>                return True<n>            else:<n>                return False<n>        <n>        n = int(n)<n>        <n>        if n > len(s) or n < 2:<n>            return 'Error!'<n>        <n>        return 'no' if not check(n) else 'yes'<n><n><n>##### Solution for Problem 2<n><n>Input: Adam buys 3 kilograms<n>Output: [24, 8, 12]<n><n>Input: Johne goes to the gym<n>Output: [16, 4]<n><n>1) 1 + 1 = 2 because one of them is 5 <n><n>2) 2 * 2 + 2 = 9 because one of them is one <n><n>3) 9 * 9 + 9 = 100 because one of them is the square root of

What is the answer?<n>Output:  Sister is happy, nobody else is sad.<n><n>Input:If there is an answer to the question, return it. Tax:   $1600.<n><n>Input:In mathematics, 11 is how many times larger than 4.  What fraction is 4 divided by 11?<n>Output: 0.364285714286<n><n>Input:Return the length of the shortest path through the vertices in a graph such that no vertex is passed more than once.<n>Output:  -11<n>

There are five times more boys as there are girls. How many boys are there?<n>Output: 10 <n><n>Input: The sum of the n-digit number is divided by 2(n+1). The quotient is 1 more than the number itself. The quotient is subtracted from zero. After that is done we multiply it by the same number that we subtracted from zero and that product results in the n-digit sum. E.g. 1001 = (1000*2-sum)(2*(n+1))=1*2+(1000-100)*2*(n+1). <n><n>Output: (2*(n+1)-n)<n>Input: It is 2000, the year of the third millennium. How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:What does a chef do when working in the evening? Choices:  A: cook dinner B: study french cooking C: taste sauce D: prepare food E: thin sauce<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input:  What kind of animal is this <n>Output: Dog<n><n>### Instruction:Input the code of this function into Leetcode 1285 Pizza Box Sorting, which is defined as follows:<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def siftSort(self, box: List[int]) -> bool:<n>        """<n>        :type box: List[int]<n>        :rtype: bool<n>        """<n><n><n>        """<n>        # 时间复杂度：O(n)<n>        # 空间复杂：O(1)<n>        1.box有序2.维护两个匹配数组 3.每次取一个，每一次用匹配数的末尾来替换 4.末尾匹配数是否满 4.不满返回返回False <n>        """<n>        def find_max_in_match():<n>            if box[10] == box[-1]:<n>                return box[box.index(box[10])-1]  # 匹配数<n>            else:<n>                return -1<n>        match_left = [find_max_in_box() for _ in range(len(box))]<n>        match_right = [find_max()<n>                    for _ in range(10)]<n><n>        for left in range(len(match_left)):<n>            if match_left[left] >= -1:<n>                continue<n>            left_item = match_left[left+1]<n>            if left_item!= -1:<n>                if left > left_item:<n>                    if(abs(left_item - box[left_item]) <= abs(left - box[match_right[left]])):<n>                        match_right[left] = left_item<n>                else:<n>                    if abs(10 - box[match_left[left+len(match_left)-1]]) <abs(10 - box[-1]):<n>                        # 如果匹配的数字在box中位于left-1后面(左侧)，则需要后移1(左侧-1

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. One kilogram of nuts costs $12 and one kilogram of dried fruit costs $8. How much did his purchases cost?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: Johns goes to the gym 3 times a week.  He spends 1 hour each day lifting weight. Additionally, he also spends a third of his weightlifting time warming up and doing cardio each day.  How many hours does he spend at the gym a week?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input: James has to refuel his plane.  It used to cost $200 to refill the tank.  He got an extra tank to double fuel capacity.  Fuel prices also went up by 20%.  How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:What can go on a football field? Choices:  A: oklahoma B: university C: college campus D: players E: yard<n>Output:		C<n><n><n>#### Solution<n>For question 1, there are two different prices for nuts and two different prices for fruits. Therefore, there are four different items, Adam paid for. So, the answer is 4.<n>For the second problem, there are 3 weightlifting sessions and 3 gym visits so the answer is 6. In this case, there are 4 different gym visits, and James used the extra tank for fuel. So, the answer for fuel cost is 50. Since players have different numbers of goals, we subtract 10, and divide the result by 2 to get the number of goals scored. This answer would be rounded up to the nearest integer, so the answer is 28. For the last question, the answer should be E because the question specifically mentions the football field and the only acceptable answer is a college campus that is within the specified area. That answer is rounded up to the next integer and so the answer becomes A.<n>

For example, "7x9" indicates that the rectangle is 7 units wide and 9 units tall. Your task is to determine the surface area and volume of a rectangle. The surface area is defined as the width times the length plus four times the width times the height, which is how much of the rectangle the four "sides" of the square take up. The volume is the length times the width times the thickness, and the thickness will be one if the rectangle is a square. For squares that are not defined with any additional units, as in "8", the thickness is one. So, in this case you would have to answer for a rectangle that is 8 units on each side and 8 units tall.<n><n>### Input Examples:<n><n>""7x9"" = surface area: 63    volume: 61 <n><n>""10x20x3"" = surface area/90 volume: 1800<n><n><n>### Instruction:<n>Ans:<n><n>```python<n>def solution(line):<n>    temp = line.split('x')<n>    length, width = temp[0].split

The code should always print the same answer line regardless of players, which is why we need to know exactly how the original code decides on who to print.<n>- Tips<n>	- 1. Create a list that stores input objects. Store the inputs from lines 4 and 5 in that list, and for the second part, the user can input a line in as a string instead (in this case, user input is not stored, but simply is interpreted using a number as the value for that line)<n>	- 2. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. Choices:  A: toy store B: story book C: great outdoors D: countryside E: wildlife refuge<n>Output:		B<n><n># Solution<n><n>from string import strip<n><n>## Multiple Choice Question<n><n>adam = 56<n><n>from collections import Counter<n>fruit_cost = Counter()<n>nut_cost = Counter(strip(adam[1:]))<n><n># Calculate total cost using cost counters<n>fruit_cost[0] = 25<n>nut_cost[0]<n><n># Add total<n>total_cost = fruit_cost[0] * 1.5<n>print(total_cost)<n><n>### Multiple Choice Solution<n><n>john = 4<n><n>david_gym = 3<n>warmup_time = 0.33<n>david_games_played = 5<n><n>print(john)<n><n>### Input<n><n>barca = 30<n><n>gary = 15<n>john = 15<n><n>from math import ceil<n><n>print(ceil(barca/6))<n><n>### Input Solution<n><n>giraffe_store_name = 'Story Book'<n>giraffe_child_calling_it 'Cow'<n><n>from collections import Chars<n>giraffes = Chars(4)<n><n>## Multiple Choce Question Solution<n>print(giraffes[0], giraffes[1], giraffes[-1])<n><n># Chars class (https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#typesmapping)<n># Returns a list of chars in a string from start to end of the string<n>### MCQ Solution

Choices:  A $1 B $10<n>Output: $10<n><n>### Instruction 2<n><n>The next 2 instruction sections are to understand a bit more about how you can input and output your solution into Lambda.<n><n>In Lambda your Input is written on the top, and Output below.<n><n>Example<n><n>Input: How many people are in your family?<n><n>Output: I am a programmer<n><n>### Input and Output<n><n>To understand what goes where in terms of input and output:<n><n>Input goes on the top and Output goes below.<n><n>To input Lambda you have multiple solutions.  In Java you do not change your input but in Lambda you need to make your input a String.<n><n>A String can be inputted either as a value, or by referencing another piece of text/instructin or another Function: <n><n>The following show examples of how you input text.<n><n>Text (not Java variable) -> "Java Programs"<n><n>Text variable:   -> String s = "Java Programs" <n><n>Function (reference to another Function): -> findFunction(1972)<n><n>Example of String reference<n><n>Input: The city with a population closest to 1 million is Mexico City.<n><n>Output: 1828904<n><n>Input: 1920%<n><n>Output: 41.5<n>### Input and output Example 2<n><n>Input and Output are always placed separately as seen above.<n><n>In the first example the input could not be referenced. This is because input is written on top and output must be placed below.<n><n>In the second example there is a number in front of the input.  <n><n>In the third example the input is an instruction (or piece of text) which is referenced by a  function: findFunction(1969). <n><n>### Instructions<n><n>The following is the full example for inputting and outputting for the question "How many people are in your fathrer's family?"<n><n>* Input: How

Every person that she talked to told her that her idea was impossible: that it was impossible to travel over water, impossibly dangerous, impossibly embarrassing, impossible to control, and that it was simply impossible to do that trick at all. Choices:  A: roof B: school C: beach D: closet E: garage<n>Output:		A<n><n>## Test Code<n><n>    int Solution::computeTotalCost(int k, string d)<n>    {<n>        int counter = 0;<n><n>        // 111111<n>        for (int i = 0; i <= k; i++)<n>            if (d[i] == "1")<n>                counter++;<n><n>        return counter;<n>    }<n><n>     int Solution::computeTotalFuelCost(int k, int refuelCost)<n>    {<n>       int totalCost = 0;<n>       int totalWeight = (k * 2);<n>       if (totalWeight == 2048)<n>            return refuelCost;<n>       <n>        int currentWeight = 0;<n>        int hoursUsed = 0;<n>        <n>        while ( true )<n>        {<n>            if (currentWeight >= 1024)<n>            {<n>                hoursUsed++;<n>                currentWeight -= 1024;   <n>            }<n>            else if (currentWeight >= (totalWeight/ 16) )<n>            {<n>                currentWeight -= (totalWeight % 16);<n>                hoursUsed ++;<n>            }<n>            totalCost += (currentWeight ) * refuelCost;<n>            <n>            if (currentTime >= hoursUsed)<n>            {<n>               break;<n>            }<n>        }<n>        <n>        return totalCost;<n>    }<n>   <n>    int Solution::findLeastUsed(std::vector < std::string > words, std::vector < int > values)<n>    {<n>         int minimumUsed = INT_MAX;<n>         int index = -1;<n>       <n>        for (int k = 0; k < words.size(); k++)<n>        {<n>            index++;<n>        }<n>       <n>        for(int i =0; i < values.size(); i++)<n>        {<n>           if(values[i] < minimumUsed)<n>           {<n>                minimumUsed = values[i];<n>                index = i;<n>           }<n>        }<n>        return index;<n>    }<n>

In this case,<n><n>\begin{dmath*}<n>P(x)=\frac{\int_a^bf(t)dt}{E(X)}<n>\end{dmath*}<n><n>By using Integral Calculus and finding a continuous extension of $f(t)$. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Adam bought 3 kilograms of nuts and 2.5 kilograms of dried fruits at a store. How much does he pay now for fuel?<n>Output: 480<n><n>Input: The number of goals scored in a game against Barca by exactly two players last season accounts for 20% of all goals scored in the league. If the players scored an equal number of goals, and the total number of goals scored in the league against Barca that season is 300, calculate the number of goals each of the two players scored.<n>Output: 30<n><n>Input:Long term consumption of beer can lead to all sorts of problems, it can be quite what? Choices:  A: water B: liquid C: foamy D: intoxicating E: harmful<n>Output:		B<n><n>#### Notes on Code:<n><n>1. Avoid doing string operations on the input string. Do use if possible.  <n>2. Instead of doing a lot string operations on the input to check the type (ie. is it all lowercase letters?), do use Regex matching against the input to validate string.<n><n>```py<n>def solution(words):<n>    return words[2].title()<n>```<n><n>```py<n>from typing import List<n><n>'''<n>https://leetcode.com/explore/interview/card/top-american-companies/159/google/136/<n><n>https://leet-code-solving-with-python-3<n><n>'''<n>def solution(words) -> List[str]:<n>    # return the second letter of each word in the input string<n>    # if there are only one word in the input list, just return the word<n>    return sorted([<n>            x[1] for w in words for x in sorted(w)<n>        ])<n><n>def solution(input_string) -> int:<n>    # return "B" if the length of the input string is 2 characters<n>    # otherise return "D"<n>    return 5 if len(input_string) == 2 else 3<n><n>def solution(words: List[str]) -> int:<n>    return sorted([words[2].title()]).index('B')<n><n>def solution(a: int) -> int:<n>	'''<n>	If a is equal to 0 or negative then return 1<n>	Otherwies return a**2<n>	'''<n>	x = (a**2) if a == 0 or a < 0 else a<n>	return (x**2) if a <= 0 or a < x else (a * 4)<n>```<n><n># Submission Link<n>[https://leetcode-cn.com/problems/check-if-a-character-string-is-a-palindrome/submissions](https://leetcode_cn.com/problem=check-if-a%E5%9C%8B-%E6%AF%88%E6%95%88-character-string-a-palindromegreater1%E5%8A%A0%E

Choices:  A: satisfied B: unnecessary C: luxury D: sufficient E: extra<n>Output:		Unnecessary<n><n>I created a C++ version and it works correctly.<n><n>```<n>#include <algorithm><n>#include <iostream><n><n>using namespace std;<n><n>int main() {<n>    const int LIMIT = 1000000;<n>    int n1, n2, m;<n>    cin >> n1 >> n2 >> m;<n>    if (n1 * n2 == m) {<n>        cout << m;<n>        return 0;<n>    }<n>    while (n1*n2 > m) {<n>        n1--;<n>        n2++;<n>    }<n>    cout << n1*n2;<n>}<n>```<n>
